Raw dev notes -- Side Project Shenanigans: Syncing & Deploying

Okay, so this past week or so has been a mix of quiet, consistent progress and a bit of a head-scratcher on the deployment front for my personal projects. It's always interesting to see what kind of small, incremental work adds up.

First up, the "halachot-orvishua" project. This is a little personal tool I built to aggregate Q&A and articles from a specific religious website (`orvishua.net`). The goal is to have all that content easily accessible, searchable, and maybe even formatted for offline reading or specific study tools. It's a passion project, really, to help me keep up with my learning. This period was pretty uneventful, which is actually a huge win. The sync script just... worked. Two separate days, it pulled in a new Q&A each time, no fuss, no errors. It's running on a cron job, and seeing those commits pop up, confirming it did its job, is surprisingly satisfying. It's the kind of "boring" success that makes you feel like you've built something robust.

Then there's the "Personal Information Hub." This is my central brain, my digital garden, where I try to pull together all my personal notes, data, and various tools into one cohesive, searchable, and useful place. It's a constant work in progress, but the idea is to have a single source of truth for my life. The main work here was around deployment. I finally got around to adding a `scripts/deploy.sh` file. This is one of those things you put off, thinking "I'll just manually run the commands," but then you do it once, twice, and realize how much time you're wasting. The script is still pretty basic, but it's a step towards proper automation.

The real struggle, and the unexpected lesson, came with that `CLAUDE.md` rule. I've been using an AI assistant (let's call it Claude, because, well, it is) to help me brainstorm and debug on this project. For some reason, I kept running into issues where I'd deploy new code, and it wouldn't seem to take effect. My go-to, blunt-force solution was often `docker restart [container_name]`. And sometimes, Claude would even suggest it. But it wasn't actually *rebuilding* the application inside the container, just restarting the existing one. It was a classic case of using the wrong tool for the job. I had to explicitly add a rule to `CLAUDE.md` saying, "Hey, when deploying new code, don't just tell me to `docker restart`. We need to actually rebuild the image or at least ensure the new code is mounted/copied correctly." It was a frustrating cycle of "why isn't this working?" until I finally pinpointed that `docker restart` isn't a deployment mechanism for *code changes* in many setups. It's for restarting the *service*. This led me down a rabbit hole of understanding `docker-compose up --build -d` better and ensuring my deployment process actually reflects code changes. It felt a bit silly to have to teach an AI (and myself, really) such a fundamental distinction, but it was a good reminder that even basic commands have nuances.

Overall, it felt good to have the sync project just hum along in the background, a testament to earlier efforts. The deployment headaches on the Hub were annoying, but ultimately led to a clearer understanding of my own deployment pipeline and how to communicate better with my AI assistant (and my future self). It's a small step towards more robust and less frustrating development.

Next up: Refine the Hub's deployment script further and integrate more data sources.
